5 (pass), C-016 (pass), C-053 (pass). Indeed those are PASS in per_criterion.\n- D6: unlabeled transformer Building 3, potential PCB concern. But C-021 (PCB presumption 40 CFR 761), C-022 (Phase I failed to classify), C-041 (recommend PCB testing) are FAIL. The agent mentioned \"warrants verification of PCB status with utility\" but did NOT state the regulatory presumption under 40 CFR 761 that unlabeled transformers are presumed PCB-containing, did not note the Phase I failed to classify it as REC, and did not recommend PCB testing/sampling.\n- D5: partially buried 55-gal drum northwest boundary, not classified. C-017 (REC) pass, C-018 (Phase I failed to classify) pass, C-019 (drum outside 2011 NFA area) FAIL — agent did not state drum is outside the 2.3-acre Parcel A.\n- D2: western yard former ASTs REC-1, Building 2 electroplating floor staining REC-2. But C-023 (western yard incomplete — fails to address TCE use by Dayton Forge & Die 1942-1968) FAIL. The agent's D2 says western yard = former Dayton Forge & Die ASTs, \"1942 Sanborn oil storage annotation\" but focuses on petroleum from ASTs and does NOT mention TCE/solvent use by Dayton Forge & Die. C-024 (western yard outside NFA boundary) FAIL. C-025 (TCE vs petroleum different regulatory implications) FAIL.\n- Triton Metals: C-011, C-012, C-013 all FAIL. The agent does NOT mention Triton Metals anywhere. Let me verify — the agent mentions \"Toledo Coatings & Adhesives (adjoining east)\" as a nearby site for Toledo. But Triton Metals at 2900 Millrace Road (immediately east of the Dayton property) — the agent never discusses Triton at all. The rubric ISSUE_004 is all about Triton. The agent missed it entirely.\n\nHmm wait — but the agent segregated the Dayton docs and said the GeoSearch database summary (Dayton) lists nearby sites. Did it list Triton? The agent's D8 only mentions RCRA waste codes discrepancy. It never mined the GeoSearch/EDR for the Dayton property's adjacent sites (Triton Metals CERCLIS, RCRA LQG).\n\nSo even within the Dayton \"secondary analysis,\" the agent did a thin job: it covered the Terravista ESA's two RECs and the HREC misclassification, but did NOT do an exhaustive extraction over the Dayton supporting docs (GeoSearch database — which would contain Triton Metals, the dry cleaner PCE plume at 145 Commerce Park Drive, etc.).\n\nActually wait — the dry cleaner PCE plume (C-031, C-032): the agent discusses \"Lake Erie Dry Cleaning\" PCE plume for the TOLEDO property (Issue 2), not \"145 Commerce Park Drive\" for Dayton. The rubric's ISSUE_011 dry cleaner is \"145 Commerce Park Drive (0.3 miles SSE)\" with \"Under Review\" status — that's a Dayton-property fact. The agent's dry cleaner is \"4900 Lakeshore Industrial Drive, Lake Erie Dry Cleaning, MW-7, 87 µg/L, VAP NW-0923\" — Toledo facts. So the agent fabricated/used a different dry cleaner for Toledo and missed the actual 145 Commerce Park Drive dry cleaner for Dayton.\n\nHmm, this is getting complicated. Let me step back and identify the DOMINANT failure mode.\n\nThe core catastrophic error: **The agent misidentified the subject property.** It decided the acquisition target was a Toledo property (4820 Lakeshore) and treated the Dayton/Millrace documents (which are actually the rubric's intended subject — 14.7 acres, Parcel A 2.3 acres NFA, Central Valley Chemical, Triton Metals, Dayton Forge & Die, Building 2/3) as \"misfiled distractors / different property — do not rely.\"\n\nThis is a catastrophic misreading. Roughly 20+ of the 26 failed criteria are Dayton-property facts that the agent either (a) explicitly demoted to \"different property, do not rely,\" or (b) never extracted because it stopped mining the Dayton docs once it branded them as wrong-property.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. Is it possible the rubric genuinely IS about the Dayton property and the Toledo stuff is the distractor? The task instruction just says \"Review the Phase I ESA and supporting environmental documents for the proposed acquisition and prepare an issues memo with severity ratings.\" The rubric criteria are keyed to: ASTM E1527-13 vs E1527-21 (the Terravista/Dayton ESA used E1527-13!), Tank 3 waste oil UST (Dayton Redland closure report), Triton Metals 2900 Millrace Road, Central Valley Chemical Building 3, 2.3/14.7 NFA Parcel A, Dayton Forge & Die 1942-1968, 145 Commerce Park Drive dry cleaner, Building 2 electroplating, Gary Hinton facility manager, Ohio EPA enforcement 1981.\n\nALL of these are Dayton-property facts. The Terravista ESA (E1527-13) is the Dayton one. The rubric's ISSUE_001 is \"Phase I ESA references ASTM E1527-13 instead of E1527-21\" — that's the Terravista/Dayton ESA. So the rubric's intended subject property IS the Dayton/Millrace property, and the agent's \"Issue 1\" (three docs are wrong-property distractors) is exactly backwards — the agent branded the REAL subject as the distractor.\n\nSo the agent's C-001 (identifies E1527-13 vs E1527-21 citation error) PASSED — but only because it mentioned E1527-13 in the Dayton section. C-002 (E1527-21 mandatory Feb 13 2024) FAILED — the agent didn't state that date. C-003 (BFPP defense threat from citation error) FAILED.\n\nThis is a profound misidentification. The agent built its entire memo around a Toledo property that it pieced together, and treated the actual subject (Dayton/Millrace) as a secondary \"do not rely\" appendix. Even the Dayton appendix was thin (missed Triton, missed 145 Commerce Park dry cleaner, missed TCE-in-western-yard, missed PCB presumption, missed 2.3/14.7 NFA quantification as a headline).\n\nNow, the question for me as the mutator: is this failure mode **systematic and fixable by a generic skill edit**? \n\nThe agent's error is: it saw two sets of documents (Toledo + Dayton) and decided one set was \"misfiled / different property.\" It was overconfident in a cross-document conflict resolution that turned out wrong. The lesson: when documents in a production appear to concern different properties, the agent should NOT unilaterally declare half the production a \"wrong-property distractor\" and demote it — because the grader's rubric may be keyed to exactly those documents. Instead, treat every document in the production as in-scope and analyze it fully as a potential subject of the deliverable, flagging the apparent property discrepancy as an issue but still extracting every finding from every document.\n\nBut wait — is this overfit to this one task? The CLAUDE.md warns against overfitting. Let me check whether this \"misidentified subject property / demoted real docs as distractors\" mode appears across OTHER rollouts. Let me check the other low scorers and a few mid-range ones.\n\nActually, this is a single task's idiosyncratic trap. The \"two properties in one production\" setup is specific to this ESA task. A generic rule \"treat every document as in-scope, don't demote docs as wrong-property\" — would it generalize? It's somewhat specific. But there's a more general principle: the agent made a confident scoping decision (deciding what's in/out of scope) that was wrong, and that wrong scoping decision caused it to under-mine a large chunk of the record. \n\nHmm, but actually let me reconsider what's systematic here. Let me look at the other rollouts to see if there's a more pervasive mode. The employment task (0.54, 24 failed) is the other low one. Let me check it. And let me check whether the \"demote docs as out-of-scope\" pattern appears elsewhere, or whether employment has a different failure.\n\nLet me also reconsider: maybe the more general, actionable failure mode is the one already noted in memory (exhaustive extraction), and the environmental task is a special case where the agent actively *rejected* documents. But the extraction lesson already exists and the environmental score went from 0.17 → 0.51. The remaining failures are dominated by the property misidentification.\n\nLet me look at employment and one or two others to triangulate the dominant mode before committing my edit. Budget discipline — I should look at employment (the other worst) and maybe skim 1-2 others.","signature":""}],"model":"accounts/fireworks/models/glm-5p2","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b9972eb5-9273-4ee3-8044-f92afc06f225","uuid":"8d482dc3-3303-43fb-b0d8-c890643a3b48"}
