s analysis of Triton's operations, contaminants of concern, hydrogeological relationship (upgradient/downgradient/cross-gradient) to the Subject Property, or current regulatory status beyond the cursory mention. FAIL if the memo does not identify any specific analytical deficiency regarding Triton.\n- C-023 ISSUE_008: Identifies incomplete analysis of western yard area: PASS if the memo identifies that while the Phase I ESA correctly classified the western yard area (stressed vegetation, darkened soil, former AST location) as a REC, the analysis is incomplete because it focuses on petroleum from ASTs but fails to address the documented trichloroethylene (TCE) use by Dayton Forge & Die (1942–1968). FAIL if the TCE/solvent component is not specifically noted as missing from the analysis.\n- C-024 ISSUE_008: Notes western yard area is outside the 2011 NFA boundary: PASS if the memo notes that the western yard area (former Dayton Forge & Die operations) falls outside the 2.3-acre Parcel A covered by the 2011 NFA letter. FAIL if this is not stated.\n- C-028 ISSUE_009: Notes vapor intrusion pathway not discussed: PASS if the memo identifies that the Phase I ESA contains no discussion of vapor intrusion as a potential exposure pathway despite the documented presence of volatile chlorinated solvents (TCE from Dayton Forge & Die, chlorinated solvents from Central Valley Chemical) and occupied buildings on-site. FAIL if vapor intrusion is not mentioned.\n- C-029 ISSUE_010: Identifies pre-1987 building department records gap: PASS if the memo identifies that the Phase I ESA reviewed City of Dayton building department records only from 1987 forward and did not attempt to obtain pre-1987 records from Montgomery County or Ohio State Archives, despite the site being in industrial use since at least 1942 (a 45-year gap). FAIL if this data gap is not raised.\n- C-030 ISSUE_010: Notes significance of 1942-1987 unreviewed period: PASS if the memo notes that the 1942–1987 period covers multiple owners/operators (Dayton Forge & Die, Millrace Industrial Park LLC, and tenants including Central Valley Chemical) and could contain records about underground structures, waste disposal, or chemical storage. FAIL if the significance of the gap period is not discussed.\n- C-031 ISSUE_011: Identifies Phase I fails to analyze potential migration of dry cleaner PCE plume toward Subject Property: PASS if the memo identifies that the former dry cleaner at 145 Commerce Park Drive (0.3 miles SSE) has a confirmed PCE groundwater plume with 'Under Review' status, and notes that the Phase I ESA does not analyze whether this plume could migrate toward the Subject Property or complicate future investigation/remediation at the site. FAIL if the dry cleaner plume is not discussed or if the Phase I's omission of migration analysis is not identified.\n=== transcript: which property did agent settle on ===\n    269 Dayton\n    210 Toledo\n     74 4820 Lakeshore\n     60 2850 Millrace\n     19 TOLEDO\n     10 2900 Millrace\n      8 DAYTON\n=== env metrics ===\n{\n  \"model\": \"glm-5p2\",\n  \"task\": \"environmental-esg/identify-issues-in-phase-one-environmental-site-assessment\",\n  \"run_id\": \"dm_train_iter1/environmental-esg_identify-issues-in-phase-one-environmental-site-assessment__2730b32105\",\n  \"turn_count\": 20,\n  \"input_tokens\": 2055938,\n  \"output_tokens\": 56476,\n  \"total_tokens\": 2112414,\n  \"cache_read_input_tokens\": 0,\n  \"cache_creation_input_tokens\": 0,\n  \"wall_clock_seconds\": 691.66,\n  \"finished_cleanly\": true,\n  \"completed_at\": \"2026-06-26T02:28:58.127924+00:00\",\n  \"documents_read\": 10,\n  \"documents_read_list\": [\n    \"phase-i-esa-report.docx\",\n    \"phase-one-esa-report.docx\",\n    \"purchase-agreement-excerpt.docx\",\n    \"lender-requirements-letter.docx\",\n    \"ohio-epa-response.docx\",\n    \"ust-closure-report-2004.docx\",\n    \"env-database-search-summary.docx\",\n    \"edr-database-summary.xlsx\",\n    \"/workspace/skills/docx/scripts/generate_from_md.py\",\n    \"/workspace/output/environmental-issues-memo.docx\"\n  ],\n  \"documents_skipped\": 0,\n  \"documents_skipped_list\": [],\n  \"total_documents\": 8,\n  \"bash_commands\": 12,\n  \"files_written\": 1,\n  \"files_edited\": 0,\n  \"glob_searches\": 1,\n  \"grep_searches\": 0\n}","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"msg_6bc5c367-718d-4a8f-8bfa-f4028b8b4b46","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"This is decisive. The rubric's \"Subject Property\" facts — Triton Metals at 2900 Millrace, Dayton Forge & Die (1942–1968), Central Valley Chemical, City of Dayton building records, 145 Commerce Park Drive dry cleaner, 2.3/14.7-acre NFA Parcel A — are all **Dayton/Millrace** facts. The agent read the Terravista `phase-one-esa-report.docx` (the Dayton/Millrace ESA, the one that is E1527-13, has Triton, Central Valley Chemical, NFA Parcel A) but decided it was a \"misfiled different property\" and demoted its entire analysis to a secondary \"DO NOT RELY\" appendix, treating the Greenfield `phase-i-esa-report.docx` (the Toledo ESA) as the primary subject.\n\nSo the agent actually analyzed BOTH, but branded the rubric's intended subject as a distractor. ~20 failed criteria are Dayton facts that the agent *did extract* (D1–D9 cover Triton, Central Valley Chemical, drum, transformer, NFA scope, E1527-13) but did **not carry through to the required form** the rubric checks: e.g., C-019 (drum outside NFA), C-024 (western yard outside NFA), C-026 (private well search), C-027 (ASTM well requirement), C-028 (vapor intrusion), C-029/030 (pre-1987 records gap), C-031/032 (dry cleaner PCE plume), C-041 (PCB testing rec), C-042 (western yard TCE rec), C-051 (well search rec), C-052 (NFA doesn't cover Building 2). These were either absent or only in the \"secondary, do-not-rely\" appendix, graded as absent.\n\nThe two worst tasks now share a deeper common failure mode that my prior \"exhaustive extraction\" lesson only partially addresses:\n\n**The agent picks a \"main\" subject/authority from the headline document and demotes or discards other documents in the production — even when those other documents are actually the controlling record or contain the bulk of the gradable findings — then treats findings sourced from the demoted documents as secondary/disposable.** In env it demoted the actual subject ESA as \"wrong property\"; in employment it never treated Greenleaf's internal settlement *policy* document as a controlling authority, so it never enforced the policy's specific mandates.\n\nLet me quickly scan the other rollouts' failed criteria to see if this \"headline-document tunnel vision / demote-the-rest\" mode recurs, so I target the dominant mode correctly."}],"model":"accounts/fireworks/models/glm-5p2","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b9972eb5-9273-4ee3-8044-f92afc06f225","uuid":"e6e5c3e5-dcf9-4df0-a457-21547bc5d26d"}
