{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"chatcmpl-tool-a717a0b6e19d5250","type":"tool_result","content":"28\t- If you *also* produce a file artifact (`.docx`, etc.), the **same substantive\n29\t  content** must appear in your text output. Treat the file as a rendering of the text,\n30\t  not a substitute for it.\n31\t\n32\t**The file you write to `output/` is itself the deliverable the grader reads.** Do **not**\n33\twrite a short \"cover note,\" \"response,\" or \"deliverables summary\" to `output/` that says\n34\tthe real content \"follows below\" or \"is set out in the final text output,\" and then put\n35\tthe actual memo/markup only in your chat message. That inversion is the single most\n36\tdamaging failure: the cover note gets graded as if it were the deliverable, every issue\n37\tand disclosure trapped in the chat is scored as absent, and a near-complete analysis\n38\tcollapses to near-zero. Instead, write the **entire** deliverable prose into the\n39\t`output/` file (your `.md` source, before generating any `.docx`), and let your final\n40\tchat message either repeat or point to that same already-complete text — never the\n41\treverse.\n42\t\n43\t**Self-check before finishing — read your own final output *and* your `output/` file as\n44\tif you are the grader:** does each issue, finding, element, and recommendation you\n45\tanalyzed appear *as its own written-out content* in the file the grader will read? If an\n46\titem appears only as *\"I addressed <topic>,\"* *\"see attached file,\"* or *\"the full\n47\tcontent is set out below\"* (with nothing actually below it in that same file), rewrite\n48\tit out in full **into that file**. A topic named in a bullet, or deferred to the chat\n49\tmessage, is not the same as the substance the rubric is checking for.\n50\t\n51\t## 2. Extract every distinct issue across the WHOLE document set — do not write a thematic essay around a few chosen headline issues\n52\t\n53\tThe most damaging subs